From cfee4a0aa844346ac790690ac013249644e412ad Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: P Praneesh <ppranees@qti.qualcomm.com>
Date: Fri, 1 Aug 2025 13:36:34 +0530
Subject: [PATCH] Upstream:DP:wifi: ath12k: fix monitor destination ring
 end_offset validation

Currently, during monitor buffer replenishment, ATH12K_DP_MON_RX_BUF_SIZE
(2048 bytes) is used to allocate the page fragment for monitor mode.
However, when reaping the monitor destination ring, the code checks the
end_offset against DP_RX_BUFFER_SIZE, whose value depends on the hardware
profile: it is 2048 for the 1G profile and 1857 for the 512M profile.

The 512M profile does not support monitor mode, but monitor destination
rings are still utilized for updating statistics. In this case, the
hardware may report end_offset values up to 2048, which are valid relative
to the monitor buffer size but exceed the 1857 limit of DP_RX_BUFFER_SIZE.
This triggers warnings such as:

ath12k_wifi7_pci 0002:01:00.0: mon_dest:
invalid offset 1879 received in mac_id 0

Using DP_RX_BUFFER_SIZE for validation is therefore incorrect and causes
these spurious warnings.

Fix this by replacing the validation checks to use
ATH12K_DP_MON_RX_BUF_SIZE consistently. This ensures end_offset is
properly checked against the true size of the monitor buffer in all
profiles, preventing unnecessary warning  messages and aligning
validation with the actual buffer allocation.

Fixes : I96784d025c9
(Upstream: DP: Add non linear skb support for monitor mode)

Patch-dependency:
0475-04-Upstream-DP-wifi-ath12k-add-page-fragment-support-in.patch

Signed-off-by: P Praneesh <ppranees@qti.qualcomm.com>
---
 drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/wifi7/dp_mon2.c | 6 +++---
 1 file changed, 3 insertions(+), 3 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/wifi7/dp_mon2.c b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/wifi7/dp_mon2.c
index 5088f60..ae3bc90 100644
--- a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/wifi7/dp_mon2.c
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath12k/wifi7/dp_mon2.c
@@ -966,13 +966,13 @@ int ath12k_dp_mon_rx_dual_ring_process(struct ath12k_pdev_dp *pdev_dp, int mac_i
 					   ATH12K_DP_MON_RX_BUF_SIZE, DMA_FROM_DEVICE);
 
 		end_offset = u32_get_bits(info0, HAL_MON_DEST_INFO0_END_OFFSET);
-		if (unlikely(end_offset > DP_RX_BUFFER_SIZE))
+		if (unlikely(end_offset > ATH12K_DP_MON_RX_BUF_SIZE))
 			ath12k_warn(dp,
 				    "mon_dest: invalid offset %u received in mac_id %d\n",
 				    end_offset, pdev_dp->mac_id);
 
-		if (unlikely(end_offset > DP_RX_BUFFER_SIZE))
-			end_offset = DP_RX_BUFFER_SIZE - 1;
+		if (unlikely(end_offset > ATH12K_DP_MON_RX_BUF_SIZE))
+			end_offset = ATH12K_DP_MON_RX_BUF_SIZE - 1;
 
 		/* The hardware reports the buffer length as (actual_length - 1),
 		 * likely due to internal indexing or alignment constraints.
-- 
